@NODE INFO "1. Overview"
@NEXT INSTALL
@PREV MAIN

@{B}@{U}A Short Overview@{UU}@{UB}

 FinalWrapper is an Arexx  macro  for  SoftWood's  famous  word  processor  Final
 Writer.  It allows you to create amazing text effects as wrapping text around an
 oval or even alongside a spiral line with just a few mouseclicks and keystrokes!

 @{B}Features:@{UB}

 Easy to use:
 - Custom requester with keyboard short-cuts for all gadgets
 - Pull down menu for preferences and further options
 - On-line AmigaGuide help
 - Uses your preferred language (currently English, Italian, German, Danish and
   Norwegian available, OS2.0+)
 - Interactive tutorial

 Makes full use of all of Final Writer's current text and graphics facilities:
 - Oval size can be defined by entering the values or simply selecting an oval
 - Text can be entered or taken from the main text or a text block/text frame
 - Unlimited text length
 - Allows any mixture of different text attributes and fonts
 - Works with rotated ovals

 Many options to manipulate the result (most of which can be combined):
 - Starting point and arc of wrapping process freely changeable
 - Spirals with increasing or decreasing radii
 - Automatic reduction of character size towards the inside of a spiral
 - Create shadow
 - Use style settings of a piece of text as a pattern for the whole text
 - Keep words in one piece
 - Additional effects with rotation of characters
 - Several methods to enhance the result (or to create more fancy effects)
 - Arexx port to allow creation of more complex effects via other Arexx macros

 A speed improvement feature formerly available only to registred  users  is  now
 included in this release. See @{"FontMaps" LINK FONTMAPS}.

  @{"Click here to look at some demo pictures" SYSTEM "Execute DemoPics/Showpics.BAT"}

 (Press Esc after each picture to continue.)


 By the way: The macro (V3.1) was reviewed in  Amiga Shopper issue 56  by  Future
 Publishing and rated 90%.
@ENDNODE
@NODE FONTMAPS "Font Maps"
@PREV INFO
@NEXT INFO

 @{B}* Font Maps:@{UB}

 @{B}What are Font Maps and what are they good for?@{UB}

 As you certainly have realized,  FinalWrapper  is  rather  slow.  Unfortunately,
 there's  not  much  I  can  do  about  that, as about 90% of the time during the
 wrapping process is absorbed by Final Writer for the drawing operations. As  you
 can  see  when  working with FinalWrapper, all characters are drawn first in the
 center of the oval to figure out their size, then they're moved to  the  correct
 place,  and  finally  rotated. The Arexx interface of Final Writer - despite all
 the great facilities it offers - lacks the commands to do all this in one step.

 That's where the Font Maps come in: There's a file for each font, where the size
 of the different characters are saved. That allows FinalWrapper to skip first of
 the three steps described above, saving about 20% of the total time.

 This archive contains these files for many fonts already  (including  all  those
 that  come  along  with  Final Writer). In case you use a font for which no such
 file exists, FinalWrapper will simply behave  as  it  used  to  (like  described
 above),  but only for those parts of the text using such fonts, the rest will of
 course benefit from the Font Maps.

 @{B}How can I create Font Maps for other fonts?@{UB}

 There's a tool included in this archive, that scans a selected directory for all
 fonts  which  don't  have  a  Font Map yet and creates one for them. (It will be
 installed as @{I}FinalWrapper:Tools/MakeFontMaps.rexx@{UI} by the Installer script.)

 First, run Final Writer. Then you can @{"start" RX FinalWrapper:Tools/MakeFontMaps.rexx}  the tool. You will be shown a file
 requester where you can select the directory containing the fonts  you  want  to
 use  (only  choose one with fonts which are suitable for Final Writer!). It will
 take quite some time to calculate (one or two minutes  per  font,  depending  on
 the comuting power of your machine - well, you  have  a  multitasking  computer,
 after  all, so that's not so terrible :-). Please note that it only works if you
 have already installed FinalWrapper! The program can be stopped at any  time  by
 simply starting it again while it's running.

 You can also run the program from the Shell with the directory as  command  line
 option.
@ENDNODE
@NODE INSTALL "2. Requirements & Installation"
@NEXT REQUESTER
@PREV INFO

@{U}@{B}System requirements@{UU}@{UB}

 All you need is an Amiga with at least OS 2.0 and 2 MByte of RAM and, of course,
 Final Writer. All other required files are included.

 Please note: You have to run RexxMast before you can run FinalWrapper  (RexxMast
 can be found in the System drawer of your Workbench).

 To run the Installer script (see below) you need the Installer (can be found  on
 Workbench  2.1+  Installer  disk,  Fish Disk 870, Final Writer Disk 1 and on the
 AmiNet).


@{U}@{B}Installation@{UU}@{UB}

 Please note that the program is no longer  Shareware  as  it  used  to  be  (see
 @{"Distribution" LINK LEGAL 4} for details).

 There's a ready made script for the Installer utility which does all the job for
 you.

 I suggest you install it to the user menu or the button strip  of  Final  Writer
 afterwards!

   @{"Start installation" SYSTEM "Installer Installation/FinalWrapper.install APPNAME FinalWrapper MINUSER AVERAGE NOPRETEND NOLOG NOPRINT LANGUAGE ?"}

 If you are new to FinalWrapper, you probably want to start  the  tutorial  macro
 "FW_Tutorial.rexx" now (after the installation, that is).


@{U}@{B}Deinstallation@{UU}@{UB}

 Once it has been installed and you don't want to use it any more you can use the
 deinstall-script to remove the entire packet.
   
   @{"Start deinstallation" SYSTEM "Installer Installation/RemFinalWrapper.install APPNAME FinalWrapper MINUSER AVERAGE NOPRETEND NOLOG NOPRINT LANGUAGE ?"}
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQUESTER "3. Using the requester"
@NEXT MENU
@PREV INSTALL

@{B}@{U}The requester@{UB}@{UU}

 Having started the macro,  you'll be prompted a requester where  you  can select
 all available options:

 @{B}@{FG SHINE}_____________________________________________________________________________@{UB}
 @{FG TEXT}@{"·" LINK CLOSE} FinalWrapper 3.22  by NDY's                                             @{"[" LINK ZIP}@{"]" LINK BACK}
 @{B}@{FG SHADOW}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{UB}
 @{"  " LINK ARC} @{"@|  Use arc: Clockwise    " LINK ARC} @{"360 " LINK ARC} ° @{"  " LINK SPIRAL} @{"@|Spiral: Outside > inside" LINK SPIRAL} @{"25  " LINK SPIRAL} %
 @{"  " LINK BEGIN} @{"@|   Begin: Absolute      " LINK BEGIN} @{"0   " LINK BEGIN} ° @{"  " LINK SIZE} @{"@| Font size: Decreasing  " LINK SIZE} @{"100 " LINK SIZE} %
 @{"  " LINK ROTATE} @{"@|   Rotate: Absolute     " LINK ROTATE} @{"0   " LINK ROTATE} ° @{"  " LINK ZOOM} @{"@|        Zoom: All       " LINK ZOOM} @{"50  " LINK ZOOM} %
 @{"@|          Join words: No           " LINK WORDMODE} @{"@|         Create shadow: No         " LINK SHADOW}
 @{"@|     Make adjustment: Nothing      " LINK ADJUST} @{"@|     Prefs: From original text     " LINK PREFS}
 @{"@|          Align: Baseline          " LINK ALIGN} @{" Edit preferences: " LINK EDITPREFS} @{"@|      Text    " LINK EDITPREFS}
 (Inch)  X: @{"     " LINK XPOS} Y: @{"      " LINK YPOS} Width: @{"      " LINK WIDTH} Height: @{"      " LINK HEIGHT} # of page: @{"     1" LINK PAGE}
 Text: @{"                                                                      " LINK TEXT}
 @{B}@{FG SHINE}_____________________________________________________________________________
 @{FG SHADOW}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{UB}
 @{FG TEXT}                               @{"  OK  " LINK OK} @{"Quit" LINK CANCEL}

 The checkbox gadget (the one with the tick) determines whether an option  is  to
 be  used  (otherwise  the  default  value  is  used).  The  cycle gadget (@|...)
 specifies the way the options work. Behind the name, you can  see  the  unit  in
 which  the  number  in  the string gadget is measured (% percent/° degrees). The
 entered numbers are automatically limited to a certain range.

 The two rows at the bottom allow you to enter the text and the dimensions of the
 oval  to  be  used.  The word in parentheses indicates the unit of these numbers
 (Inch, cm, Pica or Dots - 720 dots being one inch).
 
 Every gadget can be activated using a keyboard short-cut. The  keys  are  always
 the  first  character  of the option name@{"ą" LINK RNOTE}. Pressing this key alone has the same
 effect as clicking on the cycle gadget. If you  press  the  left  Shift  key  in
 addition, the checkbox gadget will be toggled. Finally, with the right Shift key
 you can activate the string gadget. Note that the keys only work  if  no  string
 gadget is activated!

 From inside the program,  you can use the  @{"on-line  help" LINK ONLINEHELP} function to get a short
 description of any gadget.

 There's also an interactive way of reading this part of the manual: Each  option
 has  a  demo  screen  shot  and  a  short  Arexx  macro  that  directly sets the
 appropriate options in the FinalWrapper requester. Like that you can see how the
 effects can be produced and you can try some variations by your own.
@ENDNODE
@NODE RNOTE "Note on Italian, Danish and Norwegian version"
@NEXT REQUESTER
@PREV REQUESTER

 In the Italian, Danish and Norwegian translations, some gadgets start  with  the
 same character. Therefore the keyboard shortcut is given in [brackets] when it's
 not equal to the first character.

 Also, currently all newer texts of the Danish version are in English since  Mads
 doesn't  have  the time to update his translation. If someone else is willing to
 do that, let me know.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ARC "Use arc"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV REQUESTER
@NEXT BEGIN

 This option determines the size of the sector to be used.  This  allows  you  to
 wrap  the  text  around only a part of the oval.

 Options:
 - Clockwise: The text will be written clockwise.
 - Anticlockwise: Write the text anticlockwise.

 Number: (5 to 360, up to 999 when using @{"spirals" LINK SPIRAL})
  Size of sector in degrees with 360 being the full circle, 180 the half etc.

 Default:
  Clockwise, 360 degrees

 Key:
  u

 Example:

  @{"Look here" LINK BEGIN 23}

  @{"See also here..." LINK SIZE 22}

  @{"...and here" LINK ADJUST 23}
@ENDNODE
@NODE BEGIN "Begin"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV ARC
@NEXT ROTATE
  
 With this option you can set the place where the text starts.  Normally,  it  is
 centred  relative  to  the  top  of the oval (when  writing clockwise, otherwise
 relative to the bottom). You can use this option for instance to use  a  certain
 part  of  an  oval  for  your text (or just to place the text on a circle at any
 position you want).

 Options:
 - Clockwise: Shift starting position clockwise by @{I}Number@{UI} degrees.
 - Anticlockwise: The same, but anticlockwise.
 - Absolute: Set absolute begin where 0 is at the bottom of the oval, 90  on  the
   right side, 180 at the top etc. (i.e. it's counted anticlockwise).
  
 Number: (0 to 360)
  Absolute or relative offset for the starting position in degrees.

 Default:
  Clockwise, 0 degrees

 Key:
  b

 Example:

  @{"View demo picture" LINK DemoPics/FinalWrapper.IFF/MAIN} @{"View demo picture (OS 2.0)" SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/Display DemoPics/FinalWrapper.IFF"}

  Font:     (1)  SoftSans, (2)  Worchester, (3)  Commercial Script (size  doesn't
            matter)
  Oval:     10 by 10 cm (about 4 by 4 inches)
  Settings: @{"Use arc" LINK ARC} Clockwise: 100,  Begin Clockwise: (1) 140, (2) 260, (3) 20,
            @{"Make adjustment" LINK ADJUST} Character size
  Notes:    - The image was created in three steps ((1), (2), (3))
            - Change the font with the @{"text block preferences" LINK EDITPREFS}
            - Add the dots later  (SoftSans, size 40), don't forget to switch to
              @{"Make adjustment" LINK ADJUST} Nothing for this! Use Begin clockwise 80, 320, 200.

  Try it out: @{"(1)" RX "DocRexx/Begin1.rexx"} @{"(2)" RX "DocRexx/Begin2.rexx"} @{"(3)" RX "DocRexx/Begin3.rexx"}
              @{"Dot 1" RX "DocRexx/BeginDot1.rexx"} @{"Dot 2" RX "DocRexx/BeginDot2.rexx"} @{"Dot 3" RX "DocRexx/BeginDot3.rexx"}

  @{"See also here" LINK SIZE 22}
@ENDNODE
@NODE ROTATE "Rotate"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV BEGIN
@NEXT SPIRAL
  
 Can be used to modify the rotation of the characters. Normally, they are  placed
 perpendicular to the oval/spiral.
  
 Options:
 - Clockwise: Rotate all characters by @{I}Number@{UI} degrees in addition to  the  normal
   rotation (clockwise, of course).
 - Anticlockwise: The same, but anticlockwise.
 - Absolute: All letters are rotated in the same way (i.e. they all look  in  the
   same direction).
 - Titlemode: All characters are drawn horizontally or vertically  (depending  on
   the rotation they would normally have) but their base lines run along the oval
   (simply try it out!). Only useful with relatively small  arcs  (up to 90  with
   circles, up to 120 or maybe a little more with ellipses).
  
 Number: (0 to 360)
  Absolute or relative offset for the rotation in degrees.

 Default:
  Clockwise, 0 degrees

 Key:
  r

 Example:

  @{"View demo picture" LINK DemoPics/FancyEffect.IFF/MAIN} @{"View demo picture (OS 2.0)" SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/Display DemoPics/FancyEffect.IFF"}

  Font:     SoftSans, size 34
  Oval:     10 by 10 cm (about 4 by 4 inches)
  Settings: Rotation anticlockwise: 90
  Notes:    - Add a space at the end of the text
            - Text in the middle is Letraset Plaza-Decorative, size 50

  @{"Try it out!" RX "DocRexx/Rotate.rexx"}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SPIRAL "Spiral"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV ROTATE
@NEXT SIZE
  
 Makes FinalWrapper generate a spiral instead of an oval.
  
 Options:
 - Inside > outside: Starts the spiral with a radius of  @{I}Number@{UI}  percent  of  the
   original one (i.e. a smaller one). The radius is successively increased  until
   it reaches it's original size after the text has been wrapped around the given
   arc, i.e. it  doesn't necessarily get that big if the text ends earlier. E.g.:
   if the arc is set to 360 and @{I}Number@{UI} is 50, then  the  spiral  will  start with
   half the original radii and  reach the full ones  when a full circle has  been
   passed. The size of the  characters is increased the same way unless @{"Font size" LINK SIZE}
   is specified.
 - Outside > inside: The same,  but starts  with the original radii,  making them
   smaller and smaller during progress.

 Number: (5 to 100)
  Relation between the small and the big radius of the spiral in percent.

 Default:
  Outside > inside, 100 percent (i.e. no spiral)

 Key:
  s

 Example:

 @{"View demo picture" LINK DemoPics/Spiral.IFF/MAIN} @{"View demo picture (OS 2.0)" SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/Display DemoPics/Spiral.IFF"}

  Font:     SoftSans, size 24
  Oval:     8 by 8 cm (about 3.2 by 3.2 inches)
  Settings: Spiral outside > inside: 25, @{"Make adjustment" LINK ADJUST} Arc

 @{"Try it out!" RX "DocRexx/Spiral.rexx"}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SIZE "Font size"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV SPIRAL
@NEXT ZOOM

  
 This option is used to successively change the size of the characters.
  
 Options:
 - Increasing:  The first  character is shrunk to @{I}Number@{UI} percent of it's original
   size. The following are successively increased and the  last one's size  keeps
   unchanged. Set @{I}Number@{UI} to 100  when using a @{"spiral" LINK SPIRAL} to  avoid any  change of the
   size (which is normally automatically done for spirals).
 - Decreasing: The same, but the characters'  sizes  are  decreased  rather  than
   increased

 Number: (5 to 100)
  Relation between the original and actual size of  the  first/last  character  in
  percent.

 Default:
  Decreasing, 100 percent - or: value of Spiral if given

 Key:
  f

 Example:

  @{"View demo picture" LINK DemoPics/Zoom.IFF/MAIN} @{"View demo picture (OS 2.0)" SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/Display DemoPics/Zoom.IFF"}

  Font:     Hobo Bold (size 50)
  Oval:     10 by 10 cm (about 4 by 4 inches)
  Settings: @{"Use arc" LINK ARC} Clockwise: 180, @{"Begin" LINK BEGIN} Absolute: (1) 175, (2) 0,
            @{"Make adjustment" LINK ADJUST} arc, Font Size: (1) Increasing 25, (2) Decreasing 25
  Notes:    - Was created in two steps ((1) and (2)):
            (1) with text "Growing larger and larger.."
            (2) with text ". and getting smaller again!"
            - The smaller two  versions are made with @{"Zoom" LINK ZOOM} All: 95 and 90,
            change the colour within the @{"text preferences" LINK EDITPREFS}

  Try it out: @{"(1)" RX "DocRexx/Fontsize1.rexx"} @{"(2)" RX "DocRexx/Fontsize2.rexx"}
@ENDNODE
@NODE ZOOM "Zoom"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV SIZE
@NEXT SHADOW

 The option allows you to change the size of the  created  object  automatically.
 This  is  useful  since  you  can't  change it's size afterwards. You could also
 create a smaller shadow for a previously drawn object etc.

 Options:
 - Height: The height of the oval is stretched to @{I}Number@{UI} percent of the  original
   value (so 200 means doubled height, 50 halve etc.).
 - Width: Stretches the width instead of the height.
 - All: Stretches both width and height.

 Number: (5 to 500)
  Zoom factor for the oval.

 Default:
  All, 100 percent

 Key:
  z

 Example:

  @{"Look here" LINK SIZE 22}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SHADOW "Create shadow"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV ZOOM
@NEXT ADJUST
  
 This options allows you to automatically add a shadow to the text.

 Options:
 - No: No shadow is generated.
 - Colour only: Simultaneously creates a  shadow  for the  generated  object. The
   shadow's colour is  equal to the one set in the @{"shadow preferences" LINK EDITPREFS}. The other
   styles (font, size etc.) are equal to those of the text. The shadow is  placed
   a little below and to the  right  of  the  normal  object.  The two  generated
   objects are  wholly independent, so you can  move them  around as you want and
   maybe group them when they are correctly placed.
 - Shadow prefs: The same, but the shadow has all styles as  set  in  the  shadow
   preferences.

 Key:
  s

 Example:

  @{"Look here" LINK PREFS 22}
@ENDNODE
@NODE ADJUST "Make adjustment"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV SHADOW
@NEXT PREFS
  
 The option provides you with different ways to improve the generated effects.

 Options:
 - Character size: Stretches  all  characters  to  avoid  gaps  between  them  or
   squashes them  to avoid  overlapping.  This  can make the created objects much
   better and I strongly recommend to use this for circles. Results in some fancy
   effects when used in conjunction with ellipses!
 - Character width: As above, but changes only the width.
 - Apparent width: Changes the width and makes narrow characters a bit taller and
   wide ones less  high. Like that, the text seems to have always the same height
   (narrow text looks smaller than wide text). The option is useful for ellipses.
 - Arc: Contrary to the above, this one changes the sector size  to  achieve  the
   same goal. Therefore it's only useful  if you don't need a special sector size
   (great in conjunction with the @{"Spiral" LINK SPIRAL} option!). If this  option is used, the
   @{"Use arc" LINK ARC} option  is  overridden  but it  still  determines  the  direction, the
   starting point (unless @{"Begin" LINK BEGIN} is used) and it defines the shape of the spirals.
 - Nothing: No adjustment is made.
 
 Key:
  m

 Example:

  @{"View demo picture" LINK DemoPics/FWLabel.IFF/MAIN} @{"View demo picture (OS 2.0)" SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/Display DemoPics/FWLabel.IFF"}

  Font:     Studio Bold (size doesn't matter)
  Oval:     5.7 by 3.2 cm (about 2.25 by 1.25 inches)
  Settings: @{"Use arc" LINK ARC} 190, Make adjustment: Character size
  Notes:    - Chantilly_Bold (size 9) is used for the other text

  @{"Try it out!" RX "DocRexx/Adjust.rexx"}

  @{"See also here..." LINK BEGIN 23}

  @{"...and here" LINK SPIRAL 25}
@ENDNODE
@NODE PREFS "Prefs"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV ADJUST
@NEXT WORDMODE

 This option allows you to modify the styles (font, size,  colour  etc.)  of  the
 characters.

 - From original text: All styles are those of the original text as it was  typed
   in Final Writer. If you have  entered text directly in  FinalWrapper's window,
   the  styles  are equal to  the  @{"text  preferences" LINK EDITPREFS}  (in  this  case  this  and
   the following option are equal).
 - From text preferences: Copies the styles you have set in the @{"text preferences" LINK EDITPREFS}
   for the whole text.
 - Pattern from selected text: This option can simplify your life enormously when
   creating somewhat  more  sophisticated  effects: It  takes the styles from the
   selected text and applies them on the whole text, repeating them on and on  to
   the end.

   E.g.: If two characters were selected and the first one was red and the second
   one blue,  then the first  character of the  wrap text will be red, the second
   one blue, the third one red again and so on.

 Key:
  p

 Example:

 @{"View demo picture" LINK DemoPics/Shadow.IFF/MAIN} @{"View demo picture (OS 2.0)" SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/Display DemoPics/Shadow.IFF"}

  Font:     T: Dom Casual 36, h: Dom Casual 24, e: Hobo Bold 26
  Oval:     7.5 by 7.5 cm (about 3 by 3 inches)
  Settings: Pattern from selected text, @{"Shadow" LINK SHADOW} colour only
  Notes:    - Enter the text "The" in Final Writer with the appropriate fonts and
            colours and select it before you start FinalWrapper
            - When it's done, move the shadow to the correct position
            - The shadow has the current oval border colour

  @{"Try it out!" RX "DocRexx/Shadow.rexx"}
@ENDNODE
@NODE WORDMODE "Join words"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV PREFS
@NEXT ALIGN

 If this option is selected, the words of the text are being  kept  together  and
 treated as characters (try it out, it's difficult to explain this in words!).

 Options:
 - No: Words are treated as normal.
 - Centred: The words are centred on the oval line.
 - Align left: Words start on the oval line.
 - Align right: Words end on the oval line.
 
 Key:
  j

 Example:

  @{"View demo picture" LINK DemoPics/Wordmode.IFF/MAIN} @{"View demo picture (OS 2.0)" SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/Display DemoPics/Wordmode.IFF"}

  Font:     Cabaret, size 40
  Oval:     10 by 10 cm (about 4 by 4 inches)
  Settings: @{"Use arc" LINK ARC} Clockwise: 180, @{"Begin" LINK BEGIN} Clockwise: 180,
            Join words: Centred
  Notes:    - "`" is used as apostrophe since the font doesn't have a "'"
            - The arc is a circle whith a part covered by a filled all-white polygon

  @{"Try it out!" RX "DocRexx/Join.rexx"}
@ENDNODE
@NODE ALIGN "Align"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV WORDMODE
@NEXT EDITPREFS

 Determines how the characters are placed on the oval.

 Options:
 - Baseline: All characters are placed with their baseline on the oval.
 - Centred: The characters are centred on the oval.

      **
     *  *
     *
    ***     ****
     *     *   *  ---- centre
     *     *   *
    ***     ****  ---- baseline
               *
           *   *
            ***

 Key:
  a

 Example:

  Have a look at the tutorial @{B}FW_Tutorial.rexx@{UB} for an example.
@ENDNODE
@NODE EDITPREFS "Edit preferences"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV ALIGN
@NEXT XPOS

 Allows you to edit the preferences for the text or shadow. It will pop up  Final
 Writer's  Text  preferences  requester  with  either  text or shadow preferences
 (according to the state of cycle gadget).

 Options:
 - Text: Modify text preferences.
 - Shadow: Modify shadow preferences (see also @{"Create shadow" LINK SHADOW}).

 Key:
  e
@ENDNODE
@NODE XPOS "X"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV EDITPREFS
@NEXT YPOS

 Horizontal (X) position of the oval (i.e. distance to the  left  margin  of  the
 page) measured in the unit displayed to the left of this line of gadgets.

 Key:
  x
@ENDNODE
@NODE YPOS "Y"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV XPOS
@NEXT WIDTH

 Vertical (Y) position of the oval  (i.e.  distance  to  the  top  of  the  page)
 measured in the unit displayed to the left of this line of gadgets.

 Key:
  y
@ENDNODE
@NODE WIDTH "Width"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV YPOS
@NEXT HEIGHT

 Width of the oval measured in the unit displayed to the left  of  this  line  of
 gadgets.

 Key:
  w
@ENDNODE
@NODE HEIGHT "Height"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV WIDTH
@NEXT PAGE

 Height of the oval measured in the unit displayed to the left of  this  line  of
 gadgets.

 Key:
  h
@ENDNODE
@NODE PAGE "# of page"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV HEIGHT
@NEXT TEXT

 Number of the page on which the  objects  are  to  be  drawn.  Is  automatically
 limited to available pages when drawing.

 Key:
  #
@ENDNODE
@NODE TEXT "Text"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV PAGE
@NEXT OK

 Text to be wrapped around the oval. The colour, style etc. for text  entered  in
 this gadget will be taken from the current text block settings.
 
 You can enter up to 200 characters but you can still use a longer  text, if  you
 want: just enter the words in Final Writer and put the cursor in the appropriate
 paragraph or select the passage (only the first 200 characters can be  found  in
 the  gadget, but the rest will be used all the same till you change the contents
 of the gadget).

 Key:
  t
@ENDNODE
@NODE OK "OK"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV TEXT
@NEXT CANCEL

 Starts the generation of the wrap text.

 Before clicking on "OK" for the first time, you have to select an oval plus some
 text.  This  can  be  done  at  any time: Before starting the macro or while the
 requester is open. It doesn't matter whether this is a text block or  a  passage
 of normal text. If you don't select any text, the current paragraph is used.

 You can also  enter  some  text  or  the  oval  coordinates  or  both  into  the
 appropriate gadgets instead (see @{"Requester" LINK REQUESTER}).

 Normal text has the  advantage of enabling the usage of an unlimited  number  of
 characters in  different  styles, colours, font etc. whereas entered text (up to
 200 characters) and text blocks (up to 33 characters) can only have one style@{"ą" LINK NOTE1}.

 If the oval is rotated, the wrap text will be rotated as well.

 So: Select the text, click on the "mouse-pointer gadget" and  select  the  oval.
 Or: Select  the text block, press Shift and then click on the oval@{"˛" LINK NOTE2}.
 Or: Place the cursor in the wanted paragraph and select the oval.
 Or: Enter oval coordinates and/or text in the appropriate gadgets.

 OK starts the drawing process without closing the requester. Therefore you don't
 have  to wait for the requester to pop up for the next tries. You can select any
 new oval, text block or passage of text as usual for  further  goes.  But if you
 don't  select  anything  new,  the old text/oval, will be reused, resulting in a
 shorter calculation time.  The  macro  will  automatically  rescan  the  current
 paragraph,  if  it has changed (to be exact: if either the cursor has been moved
 to another place or the length of the paragraph has been altered - so make  sure
 not to move the cursor around, if you don't want to have  FinalWrapper scan your
 paragraph again!).
  
 While drawing, the window's size is reduced and only the  title bar  is visible.
 You can click on the @{"close gadget" LINK CLOSE} at any time to abort the operation.


 Keys:
  o
  Return
@ENDNODE
@NODE CANCEL "Quit"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV OK
@NEXT CLOSE
  
 Quits the program, storing the current settings to memory.

 Keys:
  q
  Esc
@ENDNODE
@NODE CLOSE "Close gadget"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV CANCEL
@NEXT BACK
  
 If the macro is currently calculating an object, this gadget aborts the process.
 At any other time, it quits the program, storing the current settings to memory.

 Keys:
  q
  Esc
@ENDNODE
@NODE BACK "Depth gadget"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV CLOSE
@NEXT ZIP
  
 Brings the window of FW alternately to back and to  front  as  usual.  In  Final
 Wrapper, you have also a keyboard short-cut for this.
 
 Note: If the window isn't brought to front if  it  was  on  the  back  (or  vice
 versa),  just  press  the  key  again (this happens if you used the window depth
 gadget an odd number of times with the mouse).
 
 Key:
  Backspace
@ENDNODE
@NODE ZIP "Zip gadget"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV BACK
@NEXT REQUESTER
  
 Switches between the full and the minimum size of the window.

 Key:
  Space
@ENDNODE
@NODE NOTE1 "Note on usage"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV REQUESTER
@NEXT REQUESTER

 Currently case,  super-/subscript  and  underline  etc.  are  not  supported  by
 FinalWriter for text blocks.
@ENDNODE
@NODE NOTE2 "Note on usage"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV REQUESTER
@NEXT REQUESTER

 Don't select more than one oval or text  block.  FinalWrapper  being  unable  to
 figure out which object you selected first, it will simply take the oval and the
 text block with the highest  internal  number.  If  you  select  a  text  block,
 highlighted text will be ignored.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MENU "4. Using the menu"
@PREV REQUESTER
@NEXT PROGRAM
  
@{B}@{U}The menu@{UU}@{UB}

 The menu allows you to save and load your  preferred  setting  of  all  options.
 Furthermore, some less often used options can be found here.

 @{"Settings" LINK SETTINGS}
 @{"_/ Gadgets are auto-activated A G" LINK ACTIVATE}
 @{"   Final Writer Release 3     A F" LINK RELEASE}
 ---------------------------------
 @{"Load                          A L" LINK LOAD}
 @{"Save                          A S" LINK SAVE}
 @{"Reset                         A R" LINK RESET}
 @{"Defaults                      A D" LINK DEFAULTS}
 ---------------------------------
 @{"Next document                 A N" LINK NEXT}
 @{"Execute Arexx macro...        A E" LINK MACRO}
 @{"Help...                       A H" LINK HELP}
 @{"About...                      A ?" LINK ABOUT}
 @{"Quit                          A Q" LINK QUIT}

 From inside the program,  you  can  use  the  @{"on-line  help" LINK ONLINEHELP}  function  to  get a
 short description of any menu item.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETTINGS "Settings"
@TOC MENU
@PREV MENU
@NEXT ACTIVATE
  
All settings are automatically stored when leaving the macro. They are @{B}not@{UB} saved
to disk, however, they only remain active until the next reset.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ACTIVATE "Gadgets are auto-activated"
@TOC MENU
@PREV SETTINGS
@NEXT RELEASE

 If enabled, the string gadget is automatically activated, each time  you  either
 select the checkbox gadget or you change the option in the cycle gadget.

 You may want to switch this option off if you're mainly using the  keyboard.  In
 this case the string gadget is never activated unless you want to.
 
 Furthermore, the checkbox gadget is set when you  change  the  cycle  gadget  or
 the value of the string gadget (this is always done).

 Key:
  Right Amiga + g
@ENDNODE
@NODE RELEASE "Final Writer Release 3"
@TOC MENU
@PREV ACTIVATE
@NEXT LOAD

 If you are using Final Writer Release 3 and FinalWrapper generates some strange
 output, switch this option on, it will fix the problem. This is due to a bug in
 all Final Writer 3 releases older than January 3, 1994.

 Key:
  Right Amiga + f
@ENDNODE
@NODE LOAD "Load settings"
@TOC MENU
@PREV RELEASE
@NEXT SAVE

 Loads the settings stored on disk (i.e. from ENVARC:).  Use  this  if  you  have
 changed the settings and want to get your favourite ones back.

 Key:
  Right Amiga + l
@ENDNODE
@NODE SAVE "Save settings"
@TOC MENU
@PREV LOAD
@NEXT RESET
  
 Saves all current settings to disk (to ENVARC:). They will be  still  active  if
 you use FinalWrapper again after a reboot or after switching off your Amiga.

 Key:
  Right Amiga + s
@ENDNODE
@NODE RESET "Reset settings"
@TOC MENU
@PREV SAVE
@NEXT DEFAULTS

 Resets all settings to the state when you started FinalWrapper for the last time
 (i.e. it reads them from ENV:).

 Key:
  Right Amiga + r
@ENDNODE
@NODE DEFAULTS "Defaults"
@TOC MENU
@PREV RESET
@NEXT NEXT

 Resets all settings to FinalWrapper's built in defaults.

 Key:
  Right Amiga + d
@ENDNODE
@NODE NEXT "Next document"
@TOC MENU
@PREV DEFAULTS
@NEXT MACRO

 Selects the next Final Writer document. This one will be  used  by  FinalWrapper
 from now on. The name of the document will be displayed in FW's window title and
 the document window will be brought to front.

 Key:
  Right Amiga + n
@ENDNODE
@NODE MACRO "Execute Arexx macro"
@TOC MENU
@PREV NEXT
@NEXT HELP

 Displays a file requester where you can select an Arexx  macro  to be  executed.
 This  allows you to run FinalWrapper related Arexx macros (mostly beginning with
 "FW_...") with ease. (You can run the macros also from Final Writer or from  the
 Shell, of course!)
 
 The function needs the "Rx" command (usually located on your Workbench) and  the
 (rexx)reqtools.library  (are  installed by the FinalWrapper Installer script) to
 work.

 Key:
  Right Amiga + e


 The following macros are currently included:

 @{B}FW_Tutorial.rexx@{UB}
 An interactive tutorial to FinalWrapper.

 @{B}FW_CloseWindow.rexx@{UB}
 Tries to force FinalWrapper to exit. If this  doesn't  succeed,  it  closes  the
 window. In  this  case,  FinalWrapper  can't be started any more before the next
 reset. Use this macro if FinalWrapper has crashed or  can't  be  quit  with  the
 Cancel or close gadget.

 @{B}FW_ColourCycle.rexx@{UB}
 Creates a series of wrap texts  with  alternating  colours.  You  should  use  a
 different colour for oval fill and border and for the text.

 @{B}FW_MultiOval.rexx@{UB}
 Wraps a text around four ovals at once.
@ENDNODE
@NODE HELP "Help"
@TOC MENU
@PREV MACRO
@NEXT ABOUT

 Displays the contents page of the help file used for the @{"on-line help" LINK ONLINEHELP}.

 Key:
  Right Amiga + h
@ENDNODE
@NODE ABOUT "About"
@TOC MENU
@PREV HELP
@NEXT QUIT

 Shows some program information and the address of the author.

 Key: 
  Right Amiga + ?
@ENDNODE
@NODE QUIT "Quit"
@TOC MENU
@PREV ABOUT
@NEXT MENU

 Quits the program, storing the current settings to memory.

 Key:
  Right Amiga + Q
@ENDNODE
@NODE ONLINEHELP "On-line help"
@TOC REQUESTER
@PREV REQUESTER
@NEXT REQUESTER

@{B}@{U}Need help?@{UU}@{UB}

 If you want to know something about a gadget or a menu item, just press the Help
 key
 - while a menu item is highlighted to get information about that item
 - while the menu title is selected for information about the menu
 - while the mouse pointer is above a gadget for information about the gadget
 - at any other time to get information about the requester.

 You can also use the @{"Help" LINK HELP}  menu item to view the contents page of the help file.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PROGRAM "5. The Arexx port"
@PREV MENU
@NEXT BUGS

 Note: If you aren't familiar at all with Arexx, you can skip this section.

@{B}@{U}The Arexx port@{UU}@{UB}

 FinalWrapper opens a port called "FinalWrapperPort" for both window  events  and
 Arexx commands. This enables Arexx programmers to make use of the routines built
 into FinalWrapper for other macros of similar kind. If FinalWrapper is run  more
 than once, the command line arguments are passed to the running process as Arexx
 commands (if none is given, the command  "PopFront"  will  be  sent).

 E.g.:
   1> Rx FinalWrapper.rexx               (launch the macro)
   1> Rx FinalWrapper.rexx Use ZIPGAD    (shrink the window size to title bar)
   1> Rx FinalWrapper.rexx Die           (force the macro to quit)

 You can also access the macro via it's port. E.g.:
   1> Rx "ADDRESS 'FinalWrapperPort' 'Lock RESET'" (remove all remaining locks)

 Note: Arexx commands are only executed if FinalWrapper is ready, and  not  while
 it's busy doing some calculations.


 The following commands have been implemented (upper/lower case doesn't matter):

- @{B}SetVal@{UB} gadget value
  Change the value of a string or numeric gadget.
  gadget:  Short-cut of gadget name (arc,beg,rot,spl,siz,zoo,xgad,ygad,wgad,hgad,
           pgad,tgad)
  value:   New value (anything for tgad, any number for xgad,ygad,wgad,hgad, any
           integer for the rest)
- @{B}SetMode@{UB} gadget mode
  Change current entry of a cycle gadget.
  gadget:  Short-cut of gadget name (arc,beg,rot,wrd,adj,ali,spl,siz,zoo,shd,prf,
           edp)
  mode:    Entry to be displayed.  To find  out the  number of an entry,  use the
           'Default' menu item - then all cycle gadgets  show entry 0.  Count the
           number of clicks needed to get your entry - that's it's number.
- @{B}SetState@{UB} object onoff
  Select or unselect an option.
  object: Short-cut of a gadget name (arc,beg,rot,spl,siz,zoo) or a menu checkitem
          (mgad,mrel)
  onoff:   1 for on, 0 for off
- @{B}GetVal@{UB} gadget
  Read the value of a string or numeric gadget (always returns decimal points for
  numeric gadgets, never commas!).
  gadget:  Short-cut of gadget name (arc,beg,rot,spl,siz,zoo,xgad,ygad,wgad,hgad,
           pgad,tgad)
  RESULT:  Will hold the gadget's value
- @{B}GetMode@{UB} gadget
  Read current entry of a cycle gadget.
  gadget:  Short-cut of gadget name (arc,beg,rot,wrd,adj,ali,spl,siz,zoo,shd,prf,
           edp)
  RESULT:  Will hold the number of the entry (see SetMode)
- @{B}GetState@{UB} object
  Read status of an option.
  object:  Short-cut  of a  gadget name  (arc,beg,rot,spl,siz,zoo,wrd)  or a menu
           checkitem (mgad,mrel)
  RESULT:  Will hold the status of the option (0 off, 1 on)
- @{B}Use@{UB} object
  Works as if the user pressed the appropriate gadget or selected the menu item.
  gadget:  Short-cut of gadget name (okgad, cancelgad, zipgad, backgad, edp) or a
           menu item (mload,msave,mres,mdef,mabt,mhelp,mquit)
- @{B}SetStyle@{UB} char style (new as with FW3.1, negative values as with FW3.2)
  Changes the style (size, font etc.) of the given character.
  char:    Character number (1 to length of text), or 0 for all characters,-1 for
           text preferences, -2 for shadow preferences.
  style:   Styles as used for the Final Writer  command  TextBlockTypePrefs.  The
           FONT option, if present, must be the last option.  Everything after is
           interpreted as the font name.
- @{B}GetStyle@{UB} char which (new as with FW3.1, negative values as with FW3.2)
  Reads the styles (size, font etc.) of the given character.
  char:    Character number (1 to length of text),  or 0 for text preferences, -1
           for shadow preferences, -2 for default preferences from Final Writer.
  which:   Optional: Read a specific style element (e.g. FONT). Otherwise returns
           all styles in the format of GetTextBlockTypePrefs
- @{B}Set@{UB} object value
  Can be used to modify several internal values of FW.
  object:  The thing to be changed (any abbreviation of the names are accepted as
           well, e.g. "S" for "SCREEN")
  value:   New value for the object
  The following parameters are currently known:
  PORT     Change the current document. "value" is the name of the new Arexx port
           to be used. It must start with "FINALW.".  The  function  returns  the
           name of the used port (might be another one if the requested one can't
           be found) in RESULT
  SCREEN   Change the screen title. Any occurence of "%f" inside "value"  will be
           replaced  by the  current document name, "%i" by the info string (i.e.
           "FinalWrapper x.y by NDY's"). If value is omitted, the default screen
           title will be used
  WINDOW   Works as the above option but affects the window title
  ZIP      Changes the window either to the zipped (value=1) or  normal (value=0)
           size. Returns the old status in RESULT
  FONTPATH Change the default font path. This is  prepended to any font passed to
           FW  that  doesn't  contain a ":"  (Final Writer  won't find  the  font
           otherwise).  The  new path must include a ":". Returns the old path in
           RESULT. (New as with FW3.2)
- @{B}Get@{UB} object
  The counterpart of Set. Can be used to read several internal values of FW.
  object:  The  thing  to be read  (any abbreviation of the names are accepted as
           well, e.g. "S" for "SCREEN"). The parameters are the same as for  Set,
           plus the following:
  REQTOOLS Returns 1 in RESULT, if reqtools.library is available, otherwise 0.
  VERSION  Returns the  version of  FinalWrapper.  If you use any of the commands
           that were added after version 3.0, you  need to check whether there is
           a sufficiently new version installed.
  LANGUAGE The used language (new as with FW3.2)
  FONTPATH The default font path (new as with FW3.2).
- @{B}Prefs@{UB} action
  Allows you to  store the current  settings   before you modify them and restore
  them afterwards (or reset them to the defaults if no argument was given).
  action:  "STORE"/"RESET" or any abbreviation (e.g. "ST", "RES")
- @{B}PopFront@{UB}
  Brings FinalWrapper's screen and window to front and activates and unzips it.
- @{B}Die@{UB} error message (form of parameters new as with FW3.2)
  Exits FinalWrapper with an error code and/or an optional message.
  error:   Error code (optional, must be given if a message is to be displayed)
  message: Message text. Lines are separated by "|". (Optional.)
  RESULT:  The current lock counter. The action only succeeded if RESULT is 0.
- @{B}Message@{UB} message buttons title (form of parameters new as with FW3.2)
  Displays a message. The parameters must be sepparated by "\\".
  message: Message text. Lines are separated by "|".
  button:  Button text. Buttons are separated by "|" (default is "OK").
  title:   Window title. Default is FinalWrapper's default window title.
  RESULT:  Number of selected  button. The rightmost  one  has  number  zero, the
           others are numbered from left to right starting with one.
  (e.g. Message "This is a short message|on two lines\\Ok|Cancel\\My Message")
- @{B}Go@{UB}
  Starts the calculation. The command  doesn't  return before the  whole job  has
  been finished.
- @{B}Abort@{UB}
  Forces FW to abort it's current calculation. Has no  effect if  no  calculation
  is in process.
- @{B}Lock@{UB} action
  Allows you to manipulate FW's internal lock counter. If the  counter is greater
  than zero, FW cannot be quit, so you'll be  sure  it's  running  as long as you
  want (unless an error occurs).
  action:  "ON"/"OFF"/"RESET" (or any abbreviation, except "O").
           ON increases the lock counter, OFF decreases it and RESET sets it back
           to zero. You can also call it with  no parameters  to read the current
           lock counter.
           Note: Don't forget to call Lock OFF if you called Lock ON!
           Note 2: Only use Lock ON and Lock OFF inside your programs, the  other
           options are for debugging purposes only!
  RESULT:  Will always hold the current lock counter.

 If you need other commands, don't hesitate to write me!

- RC will have the following values:

 0:  Everything OK.
 1:  FW is busy. Either try it later or use "ABORT" to force an abort.
 5:  The Arexx command was incorrect (unknown, invalid parameters). In this case,
     FW  will also display a requester with the faulty  command to help you debug
     your program.
 10: FinalWrapper failed (or was terminated).

- The short-cuts for the gadgets/menu items are the following (easy to remember):
  arc:  Use arc                           spl:  Spiral
  beg:  Begin                             siz:  Font size
  rot:  Rotate                            zoo:  Zoom
  adj:  Make adjustment                   shd:  Create shadow (V3.2)
  wrd:  Join words                        prf:  Prefs (V3.2)
  ali:  Align (V3.2)                      edp:  Edit preferences (V3.2)
  xgad: X                                 ygad: Y
  wgad: Width                             hgad: Height
  pgad: # of page                         tgad: Text

  okgad:  OK                              cancelgad: Quit / window close gadget
  zipgad: Window zip (zoom) gadget        depthgad:  Window depth gadget

  mgad:  Gadgets are auto-activated       mload: Load
  mrel:  Final Writer Release 3           msave: Save
  mquit: Quit (V3.2)                      mres:  Reset
  mhelp: Help                             mdef:  Default
  mrexx: Execute Arexx macro              mabt:  About
  mnext: Next document

  (The versions given in brackets denote in which version an item first appeared
  if not already present in V3.0.)

 @{B}* Writing your own macros:@{UB}

 Your own macros should at least  contain  the  following  start-up/cleanup  code
 which will check whether FinalWrapper's port is OK and ensure it won't quit. The
 example macro "FW_Tutorial.rexx" contains a more complex initialization starting
 FinalWrapper  automatically  when it isn't yet started. Have a look at the other
 included macros as well! You are allowed to copy this  initialization  for  your
 own macros.

  /* Example macro */
  OPTIONS RESULTS
  rxport="FinalWrapperPort"
  IF ~Show("P",rxport) THEN EXIT 10
  ADDRESS VALUE rxport
  Lock ON
  Prefs STORE
  
  /* Insert your macro here */

  Prefs RESET
  Lock OFF
  EXIT

 I propose you also start the names of  your  macros  with  "FW_"  to  make  them
 distinguishable  from  the  other macros in the FWMacros drawer for the user. If
 you have written a cool macro, please send it to me! Maybe it'll be included  in
 a future release of FW!

 @{B}* Differences in the various FinalWrapper versions:@{UB}

 Due to the changes in FW, the Arexx port is neither fully backwards nor forwards
 compatible to other versions. Changes/additions to the instructions are noted at
 their desctiption, as are new gadgets/menu  items.  Various  gadgets/menu  items
 have  been  removed in newer versions. If you want to make sure you're running a
 specific version of FW, you can use the @{B}Get VERSION@{UB} command.
@ENDNODE
@NODE BUGS "6. Known bugs and limitations"
@NEXT HISTORY
@PREV PROGRAM

@{B}@{U}Known bugs and and how to find your way around them@{UU}@{UB}

 * FinalWrapper used to crash  on  rare  occasions  due  to  some  memory-freeing
 problems.  I have not yet found the reason for this. I have now removed the code
 that caused the crashes, therefore about 6.5 kByte of memory get lost each  time
 FinalWrapper  is started. I feel this is much less of a problem than the risk of
 a system crash (even if it occurs very seldom). Usually,  you'll  only  have  to
 start  FinalWrapper  once, and therefore the memory loss shouldn't really bother
 most people. I will continue to search for the reason of these crashes.

 * You shouldn't change the document while FinalWrapper  is  working  since  this
 could lead to malfunction.

 * If FinalWrapper doesn't respond to your mouse  clicks,  have  a  look  whether
 there's  an  open requester of Final Writer (such as the one that reminds you to
 save). This could block FinalWrapper when it's waiting for an answer from  Final
 Writer.

 * For flat ovals, the results aren't very amazing if the text  flows  round  the
 tight  arcs. Try the various "Adjust" options to improve this.
 
 * If the oval is rotated and the sector size is not about ±360 then the  created
 object may be placed not exactly above the oval.

 * Titlemode and Join Words don't work well together  (it doesn't make much sence
 to combine them anyway).

 * Titlemode does not produce too good results  when  used  in  combination  with
 Adjust Width.


 @{B}* Problems with older FinalWriter versions (pre-97):@{UB}

 * If you're using Final Writer version 4 or earlier, you must quit  FinalWrapper
 @{B}before@{UB}  you  quit  Final  Writer,  or  else the screen cannot be closed anymore.
 Furthermore, the  on-line  help  for  gadgets  doesn't  work  correctly  if  the
 requester  was  opened  on  Final Writer's screen and this one and the Workbench
 have different screen modes. With  other  Public  Screens  it  works  correctly,
 therefore  the  reason  for this behaviour could be the "illegal" opening of the
 requester on Final Writer's screen.  Drag  the  Workbench  down  so  that  Final
 Writer's screen appears behind it and the on-line help will work.

 * With Final Writer release 2 or 1, the characters aren't  correctly  placed  on
 the oval.


 @{B}* Configuration specific problems:@{UB}

 Finally some problems encountered by a few users.  I  was  unable  to  reproduce
 these and therefore unable to find a general solution, but nevertheless they can
 be bypassed in a more or less elegant way.

 * Problem: You get the following error message (or a similar one) when  starting
 FinalWrapper:

  Host environment not found
  in line 68
  <CALL ActivateWindow(win)>
  (errornumer 13)

 Solution: You have installed a program that loads  several  Arexx  libraries  in
 your User-startup file. Remove this program (or comment it out with a ";" at the
 beginning of the line).

 * Problem: FinalWrapper doesn't run properly when ProText is running.

 Solution: Don't run ProText and FinalWrapper at the same time :-)

 
 FinalWrapper was created and tested  using  Final  Writer  97  (21.4.97,  German
 version) on an A1200 (OS3.0, 2MB Chip, 8MB Fast, CPU MC68030, FPU 68882, HD). It
 should run with  OS3.1/2.1/2.0 and other  hardware  configurations  as  well  as
 older (and hopefully also newer) Final Writer versions.


@{B}@{U}Bug reports@{UU}@{UB}

 If you find a bug in FinalWrapper that isn't listed above, I would appreciate it
 if you wrote me about it!
 
 When an error occurs, FinalWrapper will generate a file RAM:FinalWrapperBug.Txt,
 which  contains  a  bug  report  sheet for you to fill in as well as information
 about your system that might help me to track down the source  of  the  problem.
 You can simply print that file and fill in the appropriate blanks.

 If this file  isn't generated for any reason, please use the @{"Bug report sheet" LINK BUGREPORT}.

 If you have got an e-mail address, you'll be immediately  informed  about  news.
 Otherwise please allow a couple of weeks for a reply.

 Since I currently do not plan to do any updates, I  also  don't  guarantee  that
 I'll  fix  any  bugs.  But  if you ask nicely, I might still try to do something
 about your problem ;-)

@ENDNODE
